Tuli Kupferberg and Sylvia Topp Papers

Contents

Series I. Writings, 1833, 1851-1907, 1930-2010, undated

Extent

31.44 Linear Feet in 24 record cartons, 5 manuscript boxes, 6 flat boxes
1.4 Megabytes

Scope and Contents

This series contains working files related to published and unpublished writings by Kupferberg, dating from the early 1940s to the early 2000s. Materials in this series provide a glimpse into Kupferberg's creative process and working style through his manuscripts, typescripts, notes, outlines, electronic records, and source material. His early works from the 1940s and 1950s include college coursework papers and early publication submissions, many using variations on his name, including Norman Kupferberg, Naftali Kupferberg, Norman Cooper, Arab Kupa, and Tuli Kupferberg. Of note is an unpublished manuscript from the 1940s, The Novel, which is believed to be an autobiographical account of Kupferberg's teen and college years. Scrapbooks within this series contain clippings of some of his early published writings. Kupferberg often self-published through his company, Birth Press, including his popular parody song lyric book, Listen to the Mockingbird, (1973) of which this series includes his illustrations, drafts, and source material for all five editions. This series also contains images, notes, and reviews for the books As They Were (1973) and As They Were Too (1979), which were in collaboration with Sylvia Topp. Chapter outlines and drafts for his unpublished novel The Fucks (inspired by Kupferberg's band The Fugs) can also be found in this series. He also wrote for many underground and mainstream publications, including a column, Dope Lore, for High Times magazine, of which this series contains source material, and reader letters. A large collection of notes, drafts, and source material related to Kupferberg's poems and newspoems, which were poems inspired by news clippings, can be found in this series, ranging in date from the 1940s to the early 2000s. Kupferberg often accumulated research information for his writings on notecards, and this series contains cards for 1001 Ways to Make Love and notes for First Glance: Childhood Creations of the Famous, as well as ideas for Dope Lore. Small notebooks kept throughout his life in which he recording writing ideas, quotes, and general thoughts can also be found in this series. Material specifically related to Kupferberg's Birth Press publications can also be found in Series V.

Arrangement

Folders are arranged in the original order of the donor: alphabetical by the writing's title or subject. Some of these files were alphabetized by a definite/indefinite article, and sometimes following the article (ie. the, a). Folders for Listen to the Mockingbird are grouped by edition (there were five) and alphabetically within each edition. The poem and newspoem files were left as originally filed by the donor, with the majority of the poems grouped under letters of the alphabet, rather than individual titles. Only a small group of the poem files were listed by individual titles. The newspoem files were also left in their original order, with minimal desciption of individual works. Kupferberg's collection of notecards, notebooks, and scrapbooks come at the end of the series inventory after the writings files.

langmaterial

English

Series II. Cartoons/Collages, 1964, 1970-2008, undated

Extent

20 Linear Feet in .5 record carton, 44 manuscript boxes, 1 flat folder, 3 oversize flat folders, 1 flat-file folder

Scope and Contents

This series contains over 40 years of files related to Kupferberg's cartoons and collages including drafts, original artworks, photocopies of artworks, notes, and source material. Although he began drawing in the 1950s, the majority of the material in this series dates from the 1970s through the 2000s. Most artworks include captions with witty puns, which evolved into Kupferberg's signature style: a combination of captions, line drawings, collage elements (text and images taken from books and newsprint), and song lyrics. These artworks can be found throughout Kupferberg and Sylvia Topp's Birth Press publications, but were also published in smaller, New York City-based as well as national publications. Most of the artworks in this series are politically-themed, including humorous commentary on war; religion; US Presidents Ronald Reagan, George Bush, and Bill Clinton; the Vietnam War; the Iraq War; Judaism; and Nazism. Sex and sports are also recurring themes in works within this series. Notated files related to his publication Old Fucks at Home and his lifelong unpublished project, Book of Perverbs can also be found in this series.

Arrangement

The first group of files in this series have been left in their original order, followed by those which were re-arranged previously by an adjunct into a succession of alphabetical runs, and the arrangement ends with files pulled from other sections of the collection and placed in this series.

Processing Information

The processing archivist kept material in original order if it was known to be intact, to illustrate Kupferberg's filing system and thought process. None of the files were placed in chronological or alphabetical order, but left as they were found. Original folder titles assigned by Kupferberg were kept when possible. Kupferberg assigned the folder titles, which were often sections of text found within the work and not an official title of the piece. Additionally, some files were grouped by Kupferberg under subject headings, which were notated and added to folder titles when possible. Multiple, duplicate copies of the same work with different titles were scattered throughout this series. If a title was difficult to read or abbreviated incomprehensibly, the title was transcribed and placed in brackets on the folder, usually below the original. If the original folder was in usable condition, it was kept, otherwise material was refoldered in legal-sized acid-free folders. Unusable folders with distinguishing marks on the exterior were kept along with their contents and placed in acid-free folders. Source material within folders varied widely in date, some as early as the 1800s, however the files were notated only with the work's actual execution/submission to publications date/s.

Series III. The Fugs, 1964-2008, undated

Extent

12 Linear Feet in 10 manuscript boxes, 1 tall manuscript box, 2 hinged-ring binder boxes, 3 flat boxes, 6 oversize folders, 1 flat-file folder
111 audiocassettes
10 sound discs (vinyl)
4 sound discs (cd)

Scope and Contents

This series contains setlists; announcements; clippings; sound recordings; photographs; and posters related to the band, The Fugs, who performed in various New York clubs during the 1960s and 1970s, including The Bridge, The Bowery Ballroom, and The Knitting Factory. Tour planning files, along with announcements and posters from the 1960s through the 2000s illustrate The Fugs' world-wide popularity. Audiocassettes, vinyl discs, and CDs contain recordings of the band's appearances and concerts, as well as interviews, local New York events, and their albums. Of note are recordings from the 1990 Fugs Orgy on WHRB in Cambridge, MA, and their 1994 Real Woodstock Festival concert. An audiocassette of a Bob Dylan radio interview from the 1960s in which he mentions The Fugs can also be found in this series. Scripts and recordings of songs related to a proposed Fugs-inspired movie project Fingers in the Sun, written by Kupferberg and fellow band member Ed Sanders can also be found in this series. See also Series VIII for Fug fan mail and Series VII for additional clippings and articles.

Arrangement

This series has been arranged in alphabetical order by file title.

Processing Information

Original folders and their titles were kept when possible, while folders in poor condition were replaced with legal, acid-free folders. Kupferberg arranged a portion of the files into alphabetical order and the processing archivist followed this arrangement, placing any loose files within this arrangement. Photographs in this series were foldered in smaller groups to alleviate their excessive curling were and were arranged in chronological order. Audiovisual material was placed in appropriate housing, replacing damaged cases when necessary.

Series IV. Projects, 1959-2009, undated

Scope and Contents

This series contains files related to Kupferberg's numerous performance, theatrical, and musical projects, including his involvement in the Revolting Theater; Revolting News television show; and local and international appearances. Kupferberg's parasongs (a song using new and original lyrics set to an older, popular melody) were often used during solo and group performances as well as printed in a variety of publications. Parasong files make up the largest section of this series, containing lyric sheets, notes and source material. These files overlap with parasongs found in files for various editions of Kupferberg and Sylvia Topp's book, Listen to the Mockingbird, found in Series I. and V. This series also contains performance recordings; recorded sound effects; setlists; photographs; posters; clippings; and event announcements for the Revolting Theater group, dating from the early 1970s to the 2000s. Posters, flyers, clippings, and sound recordings (some unreleased) related to Kupferberg's solo appearances such as poetry readings and musical events can also be found in this series. Photographs in this series include street scenes around Lower Manhattan during the 1960s, images of friends, political protests, and parties. Kupferberg performance photographs at poetry readings, concerts, etc., are also found in this series. A significant number of files on the Vagabond's Codebook, possibly a failing book project taken over by Kupferberg or Sylvia Topp can also be found in this series. The series also contains sound recordings of Kupferberg readings and concerts; Revolting News television episode from 2008; interviews; songs; answering machine messages; and audio letters from friends. These recordings can be found on audiocassettes, audio reels, and record albums. This series also contains 16mm film titled Good Soldier.

Arrangement

Files were arranged in alphabetical order by the processing archivist.

Appraisal

Thirteen audio cassettes were deaccessioned due to excessive bug and dirt infestation. One blank audio reel and three 16mm film reels were also deaccessioned. Additionally, one audio reel not created by Kupferberg was deemed out of scope and deaccessioned.

Processing Information

Original folders and their titles were retained when possible. Folders in poor condition were replaced with legal, acid-free folders. The parasong/song lyric files were left in their original order.

Series V. Birth Press/Vanity Press, 1874, 1890, 1948-2008, undated1950-1985

Extent

16.50 Linear Feet in 7 record cartons, 1 manuscript box, 2 flat boxes, 4 oversize flat boxes, 2 flat-file folders

Scope and Contents

This series contains material generated by Birth Press (sometimes referred to as Vanity Press), a small publishing company started in the 1950s by Tuli Kupferberg and Sylvia Topp, in which publications were assembled in their apartment, then distributed to local bookstores or sold on the street. The 50+ works published over the years through Birth Press were a collaborative effort, with Kupferberg as primary writer and Topp as editor and designer. This series contains working files for these works, including edited manuscripts; source material; photographs/illustrations; and layout plates/negatives. Many of their publications, including their ﬁrst title, Birth featured works by Allen Ginsberg, Diane Di Prima, LeRoi Jones, and others in and around the Beat scene, as well as the ﬁrst published work of Ted Joans. This series also contains a notable collection of original children's drawings and writings, as well as general research, gathered for use in their magazine Swing, as well as in their books, As They Were (1973), and As They Were Too (1979). Layout pages, photographs, correspondence, and planning files for First Glance: Childhood Creations of the Famous can also be found in this series. Correspondence related to Birth Press from the 1950s through the late 1990s illustrates the personalities of their readership and popularity of their publications within their lower-Manhattan neighborhood, as well as on a national and international level, seen in the volume of comments and requests for subscriptions and individual publications found in these files. The correspondence files also include submissions and interactions with writers/contributors for publications Birth, Swing, and Yeah.

Arrangement

Arranged in alphabetical order by publication title, followed by correspondence files, which are arranged chronologically. Original, notated folders for Book of Perverbs were retained with the folder contents and placed in acid-free folders.

Series VI. Research and Source Material, 1821-20101960-1995

Extent

70 Linear Feet in 50 record cartons, 23 manuscript boxes, 1 flat folder, 2 flat boxes, 5 oversize flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This series includes research and subject files, as well as limited print and mainstream publications, all collected or purchased by Kupferberg. This material was used as inspiration and content for his musical and theatrical performances; writings; and artworks. Material within this series overlaps with other series in this collection, especially Series I-V.

Arrangement

Organized into two subseries:

Subseries A. Research and Subject Files

Subseries B. Source Publications

Material is arranged alphabetically by folder title.

Subseries A. Research and Subject files, 1821-20101960-1995

Extent

52 Linear Feet in 50 record cartons, 1 flat box, 1 flat folder, 2 oversize flat boxes

Scope and Contents

This subseries includes subject and research files containing news clippings and articles; handwritten notes; political cartoons; illustrations and advertisements; and original writings related to Kupferberg's various projects. Major subjects include children, sex, counterculture of the 1960s, death, drugs, medicine, music, Vietnam War resistance, and war. This series also contains a collection of vintage advertisements dating from the early 19th and 20th century, which were frequently used as graphics in Birth Press publications, Revolting Theater skits, in collages/cartoons, and on Revolting News television episodes.

Arrangement

Folders were arranged alphabetically by folder title, followed by chronological general folders.

Processing Information

Kupferberg kept multiple runs of alphabetical subject files. For ease of discovery, the processing archivist arranged the files in a continuous alphabetical run, using original folder titles when possible. Untitled/unfoldered materials were grouped together in "general" folders at the end of the series.

31142063506128box: 103, folder: 1-9 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)
31142063506136box: 102, folder: 1-6 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)
31142063412269box: 40, folder: 1-6 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)

Subseries B. Source Publications, 1863, 1869, 1899-1900, 1923, 1933-2009, undated

Extent

12 Linear Feet in 22 manuscript boxes, 1 flat box, 3 oversize boxes

Scope and Contents

This series includes publications used by Kuperferberg and Topp for source material for writings, collages, music, and cartoons. These publications include local New York zines, underground newspapers, small press literary magazines, and international journals. Some publication topics include anarchy, politics, protests, sex, art, and humor. Publication dates range from the mid-1800s to 2009. The majority were published in the 1970s-1990s.

Arrangement

This series is listed alphabetically.

Appraisal

Duplicate copies as well as issues of publications already held within Bobst Library and the Special Collections Libraries were deaccessioned.

Processing Information

Publications were grouped by format size, foldered, and labeled. The processing archivist arranged the files within each publication size in alphabetical order.

31142063261963box: 236, folder: 5 (Material Type: mixed materials)

Series VII. Publications, 1942-2008, undated

Extent

55 Linear Feet in 25 manuscript boxes, 3 flat boxes, and 25 oversize boxes

Scope and Contents

This series contains publications related to Kupferberg's projects throughout his life including articles written by and about him; his cartoons and collages; poetry reading and performance announcements; and interviews. Fug concert announcements, album reviews, and interviews with band members can also be found in this series. Revolting Theater show announcements and literary appearances around New York can also be found in the publications. This series contains many New York-related titles including New York Arts Weekly, Soho Weekly News, New York Press, Downtown, The Village Voice, and The East Village Other. Wider distribution publications can also be found in this series, including National Lampoon, Against the Current, Screw, and WIN. Of note is Kupferberg's popular High Times columns, both Dr. Fuck, and Dope Lore. Fan mail for these columns can be found in Series VIII. There is a notable collection of smaller press/zines in this series including Crawdaddy, Inside Joke, Other Scenes and Public Illuminations Magazine.

Arrangement

Publications are arranged alphabetically within each format size grouping. Publications are not listed individually, but by the alphabetical range of titles within each box.

Appraisal

Duplicate copies of publications were deaccessioned.

Processing Information

The processing archivist foldered all publications, housing them by size, and alphabetizing them within each publication size. Page numbers and subject of reference were often notated on the front page of publications, or on a small slip of paper within. Post-it notes found on the publications were photocopied and placed within. Notes or brief letters found within the publications were retained to give context.

31142063594827box: 289, folder: 1-5 (Material Type: Mixed Materials)

Series VIII. Correspondence, 1949-2010, undated

Extent

9 Linear Feet in 9 record cartons
1.4 Megabytes

Scope and Contents

This series contains letters from friends and colleagues, many who were notable political figures, artists, writers involved in the arts scene in New York and internationally during the 1960s through 1990s, including Sam Abrams, Al Aronowitz, Coby Batty, Lenni Brenner, Noam Chomsky, Diane di Prima, Royston Ellis, Lawrence Ferlinghetti, Allen Ginsberg, Urban Gwerder, Harry Hooton, Ted Joans, LeRoi Jones, Walter Lowenfels, Arthur Moyse, Anais Nin, Genesis P-Orridge, Sparrow, Ed Sanders, Rebby Sharp, Robin Tatham, Allen Tobias, and Judith Wehlau. This series also contains writing and music samples from admirers as well as reader responses and suggestions to Kupferberg's works. A significant section of the series contains general correspondence in paper and electronic records, grouped by decade, received from friends, fans, and publishers. This series also contains fan mail for his band The Fugs and for Kupferberg himself. The largest portion of the fan mail dates from the 1960s and documents the thoughts, issues, and activities of young people during the 1960s, living in the United States, as well as internationally. Kupferberg appears to have responded regularly to these fan letters. Also of note in this series are responses and reader suggestions regarding Kupferberg's Dope Lore column, which ran through the early 1980s and was primarily about drug use. The letters within this series are mostly those received by Kupferberg, except for a few folders specifically noted as written by him, and a few of his notes and responses scattered throughout the files. This series also includes a small amount of limited-circulation publications, usually attached to letters from publishers with whom Kupferberg exchanged his own publications. Correspondence regarding Birth Press can be found in Series V.

Arrangement

Folders were arranged alphabetically by sender's last name, company name, or subject title. Archivist-arranged general correspondence files were grouped by decade following the individual files. Some correspondents within the general files may also have individual files within this series.

Processing Information

Folder titles were assigned by Kupferberg and/or family members who assisted in the packing of the papers for their transfer to NYU. For the most part, original titles kept by the processing archivist. Some files include demo audio cassette tapes or CDs of music, etc. from various senders. These items are retained as artifacts and will remain with the correspondence and not be digitized.

Series IX. Performance Props and Costumes, circa 1960s-2010

Extent

25 Linear Feet in 1 manuscript box, 11 record cartons, 9 flat boxes, 1 oversize file folder, 1 oversize box, 2 musical instruments, 1 toy gun, 1 suitcase

Scope and Contents

This series contains clothing, musical instruments, and toys used by Kupferberg in his performances with his band the Fugs, his performing group Revolting Theater, Revolting News television episodes, and solo performances. Army uniforms and helmets; flags; hats; small musical instruments; masks; novelty toys; toy soldiers; t-shirts with slogans; and toy weapons in this series date from the 1960s to 2010. Two of Kupferberg's handmade "erectorines" (a broomstick with hundreds of bottle caps nailed onto it), as well as a black suitcase he used to transport props to performances can also be found in this series.

Arrangement

Materials in this series were grouped by the processing archivist into boxes by item type when possible.

Appraisal

Items found too badly damaged or stained were deaccessioned by the processing archivist. Deaccessioned material includes bug-infested clothing, heavily stained t-shirts, rusted metal, melted candy, and broken, sharp objects.

Processing Information

Material was sorted into similar item groupings when possible and housed according to size.
